# flowresistance dampens the oscillation proportionally to velocity. Two identical
# springs -- one with flowresistance=0.5, one frictionless -- diverge once the
# mass is moving: at t2 the damped one has a lower velocity. Pins the qualitative
# "friction slows it down" (values are integrator-specific, SPEC-GAP as in
# initial-fall).
tickrate 10
patch <<<
[spring]
    flowresistance = 0.5
    position       = O1
    velocity       = O2

[spring]
    position       = O3
    velocity       = O4
>>>
# t1: both still identical (velocity was 0, so the velocity-proportional damping
# has no effect yet) -> v=0.1
@1 expect O2 0.01 tol 1e-6
@1 expect O4 0.01 tol 1e-6
# t2: damped a = 1 - 0.01 - 0.5*0.1 = 0.94 -> v=0.194 ; frictionless v=0.199
@2 expect O2 0.0194 tol 1e-6
@2 expect O4 0.0199 tol 1e-6
